''Barbarian II'' received praise for its audio, mostly for the versions on more powerful platforms.  Reviewers of ''[[The Games Machine]]'' pointed out that the "most remarkable feature of the ST version is its crystal clear sampled effects".<ref name=machine17>{{cite journal
 | author = The Games Machine staff
 |date=April 1989
 | title = Version Update&mdash;Barbarian II
 | journal = The Games Machine
 | issue = 17
 | page = 45
 | publisher = Newsfield Publications
 | location = Shropshire, United Kingdom
 | issn = 0954-8092 }}
</ref> ''[[Zzap!64]]''{{'}}s staff and ''[[Computer and Video Games]]''{{'}}s [[Julian Rignall]] were impressed with the digital thuds and whacks produced on the Commodore 64, and particularly the rendition of a certain monster's laughter.<ref name=cvg82 /><ref name=zzap40 /> Mike Pattenden of ''[[Commodore User|CU Amiga]]'' claimed the "manic clucking of the mutant chicken would be enough to send [the player] running in the opposite direction".<ref name=cu89 /> Although rating the audio-visual components of the Amiga version on par with that for the [[Atari ST]], Pattenden and reviewers from ''The Game Machine'' felt the flashy introductory sequence on the Amiga made it stand out;<ref name=cu89 /><ref name=machine23>{{cite journal
 | author = The Games Machine staff
 |date=October 1989
 | title = Version Update&mdash;Barbarian II
 | journal = The Games Machine
 | issue = 23
 | page = 91
 | publisher = Newsfield Publications
 | location = Shropshire, United Kingdom
 | issn = 0954-8092 }}
</ref> Tony Horgan of ''[[Amiga User International]]'' called it the best introduction he has seen in Amiga games.<ref name=aui />

Although some reviewers were less than impressed with the colour-scheme on systems such as the ZX Spectrum<ref name=sinuser81 /> the colours and large detailed sprites on the higher-end platforms won their acclaim. The animation of the characters also captured their attention.  Tommy Nash of ''[[Your Sinclair]]'' hailed it as "first class",<ref name=ys32 /> while [[Paul Glancey]] of ''Zzap!64'' called the sprites "beautifully defined" and "realistically animated".<ref name=zzap40 />  Similar accolades were given by other reviewers.<ref name=cvg82 /><ref name=cu08 /><ref name=zzap40 /><ref>{{cite journal
 | last = Roberts
 | first = Nick
 |date=December 1990
 | title = Reviews&mdash;Barbarian II
 | journal = Crash
 | issue = 53
 | page = 19
 | publisher = Newsfield Publications
 | location = Ludlow, United Kingdom
 | issn = 0954-8661 }}
</ref> The staff of ''The Games Machine'' were "constantly [amazed]" at the designs of the monsters in the game.<ref name=machine9 />

Several reviewers had a common complaint about the game. As the difference between executing an attack and a movement was the pressing of the joystick button, they were irked to find their characters frequently switching directions instead of attacking with a low slash.<ref name=zzap67 /><ref name=cu08 /><ref name=sinuser81 /> Their frustration was increased when the protagonist took damage from enemy attacks as he or she executes the unintentional command to change facing.<ref name=sinuser81 /> Chris Jenkins, however, praised the game for responsive joystick controls in his review for ''[[Sinclair User]]''.<ref>{{cite journal
 | last = Jenkins
 | first = Chris
 |date=November 1990
 | title = Review&mdash;Barbarian II
 | journal = Sinclair User
 | issue = 105
 | pages = 60&ndash;61
 | publisher = EMAP
 | location = London, United Kingdom
 | issn = 0262-5458 }}
</ref> Paul Lakin of Zero pointed out that the flick-screen presentation could lead to confusing situations in combat as the protagonist retreats across an exit and appears at the other end of the screen.<ref>{{cite journal
 | last = Lakin
 | first = Paul
 |date=February 1990
 | title = Déjà Vu
 | journal =[[Zero (video game magazine)|Zero]]
 | issue = 4
 | page = 72
 | publisher = Dennis Publishing
 | location = London, United Kingdom
 | issn = 0957-9303 }}
</ref> Horgan had another grouse with the combat, moaning the loss of simplicity from the ''Barbarian'' series. According to him, while players could enjoy the first ''Barbarian'' game without much effort, intense practise was needed to defeat the monsters in the second game.<ref name=aui />

The change in combat systems was not the only difference between ''Barbarian II'' and its predecessor that influenced reviewers' opinions about the sequel. The first ''Barbarian'' game was enjoyed by reviewers for providing exciting head-to-head action between two players. ''Barbarian II'' abandoned this, setting up an adventuring experience for the single player. Jim Douglas, reviewing for ''Sinclair User'', doubted that players who were looking for quick action would appreciate plotting a path through the maze to reach the final goal.<ref name=sinuser81 /> ''Your Sinclair''{{'}}s Marcus Berkmann felt the two genres&mdash;slash 'em up and arcade adventure&mdash;were "fundamentally incompatible", agreeing with Douglas that the maze was a distraction.<ref name=ysreview>{{cite journal
 | last = Berkmann
 | first = Marcus
 |date=January 1989
 | title = Reviews: Barbarian II
 | journal = [[Your Sinclair]]
 | issue = 37
 | page = 49
 | url = https://spectrumcomputing.co.uk/page.php?issue_id=258&page=49
 | access-date = 28 January 2023
 | publisher = Dennis Publishing
 | location = London, United Kingdom
 | issn = 0269-6983 }}
</ref> ''[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]''{{'}}s reviewers, however, felt the combination of genres made the game interesting.<ref name=crash60 /> James Price wrote in ''[[Amiga Force]]'' that the adventuring element and unending number of enemies made ''Barbarian II'' a far better game than the first,<ref>{{cite journal
 | last = Price
 | first = James
 |date=May 1993
 | title = Feature
 | journal = [[Amiga Force]]
 | issue = 5
 | page = 16
 | publisher = [[Europress|Europress Impact]]
 | location = United Kingdom
 | issn = 0967-702X }}
</ref> while ''The Games Machine''{{'}}s staff said the expanded menagerie of foes adequately made up for a reduction in combat moves.<ref name=machine9 />

In their review for ''Dragon'' magazine, the Lessers called ''Axe of Rage'' "an engrossing slash 'n hack that'll please most arcaders."<ref name=dragon150 /> ''Zzap!64''{{'}}s reviewers were unanimous in recommending ''Barbarian II'' to their readers;<ref name=zzap40 /> however, two years later in a re-review, the magazine's staff said the game has aged badly, finding the gameplay "lot more crude and clichéd" and of dubious replay value.<ref name=zzap67 /> Martyn Carroll concurred in his article for ''[[Retro Gamer]]'', 17&nbsp;years after the game's release, calling ''Barbarian II'' "hugely disappointing" for "[messing] up almost everything that was great about the first game."<ref name=retro23 /> Brown and Palace Software's co-founder Richard Leinfellner admitted as much; they said they had mixed feelings about ''Barbarian II'', thinking the idea of a simple fun game was lost by stuffing too many features into it.<ref name=russell>{{cite magazine
